@NODE Intro "Introduction"

                                  ..
                             .---:  :---------.
                             |   ····         |
                            [%] iNTRODUCTiON [%]
                             |         ....   |
                             `---------:  :---'
                                        ··

FAME  util  to  check number of inactive users over x number of days.  This
allows  the  sysop  to maintain a steady userbase and delete accounts where
                              they see fit :)

This version checks the Deleted_Or_Not flag properly so won't re-list any
users that have already been deleted.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Install "Installation"

                                  ..
                             .---:  :---------.
                             |   ····         |
                            [%] iNSTALLATiON [%]
                             |         ....   |
                             `---------:  :---'
                                        ··

Just  copy  this  to  any  directory  you  store  your bbs utilities and run
whenever  you  wish.  There are two versions, a standard version and the 020
version. Rename the command to "udclean" and put it wherever.  Simple eh? :)
@ENDNODE
@NODE Usage "Usage"

                               ..
                          .---:  :--------------.
                          |   ····              |
                         [%] USiNG THE PROGRAM [%]
                          |              ....   |
                          `--------------:  :---'
                                          ··

Usage: UDClean <userdata> <days> <header> <footer> [<ignore>]

Example: UDClean FAME:user.data 90 Header.txt Footer.txt Ignore.txt

The  ignore  file  is a list of users that you wish to ignore no matter how
many  days it has been since their last call, perhaps members of your group
    who are at university or don't have regular access to a modem etc.

You  can  use  it  as a bulletin or just from the cli to keep an eye on who
              isn't supporting your board on a regular basis.
@ENDNODE
